<br>
In full groups, I am always the healer, no exceptions. There just isn't anyone else to do it, and I don't mind it a bit, I really do enjoy it actually and think I'm quite good at it. However, when I'm at full mana, and we are only taking single pull after single pull, I feel like excess baggage because there really isn't much for me to do. I snare and throw a damage sheild on the tanks, but these take hardly any mana at all.  I always feel like there is something else I should be doing. I do keep everyone buffed with Skin like Steel as well and still have alot of time on my hands.<br>
<br>
What I've come to now is to not even bother with DoT's in a full group,  but if there are only a few of us and our tank is a Ranger, then I DoT them with Creeping Crud, it usually wears off before the fight is even over so it's worth it. In dungeon situations it's just a mana burner, however, I do always keep a DoT memmed just in case.  I do like to throw off Lightening if I'm full mana and it's a single pull but I always make sure it's ok with my group before the fight starts, noone has had a problem with it yet, again, as long as I'm full mana and not when it's a big pull, big pulls, all my mana goes toward snaring and healing. <br>
<br>
And I agree with Kimaya, I always keep a lower level spell memmed. If I'm the sole healer, I keep light healing memmed as well. If I don't have enough mana for Healing, I usually can go for a Light Healing and sometimes even that little bit can keep someone alive long enough to get to zone in a really bad situation. <br>
<br>
I've finally come to the realization that everything is situational for Druids since we're competent in alot of things but master of none of them, when it comes to groups. As much as it is frustrating to find the best use of my skills when in a new group, it has really been a huge learning experience on how to work with different classes.  <p>Narie<br>
The Bumbling Half Elf Druid <br>
Now Debuting in her 26th season</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uimpatiens.showPublicProfile?language=EN>impatiens</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/22/02 9:53:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=398.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Effective roleplaying</span><hr size=1> As far as class roles/stereotypes the above advice by Steeltoe is excellent. Those who would best be served by it are those who have not played their current class before. The 'old hands' generally know when they can break the rules. I played a high end cleric on my old server and would often melee when mana was above 90% and we did not have any on ice waiting to be killed. I was mostly trying to raise my defense and offense for those truly awful situations when they might actually come in handy. Oh, and also to kill those stupid bixies quickly. I don't think anyone ever had lower Bixie faction than my old character. To my mind a responsible player learns her primary function first and experiments on 'down' or free time. And ask your group if its ok to melee, if your a caster or otherwise act crazy.<br>
<br>
Yes this is a roleplaying server. Learn to play your role. Then learn to improvise. As a cleric I had to substitue as an enchanter (with root), melee (may Tunare have mercy on us all), puller (complete nightmare) and nuker (fun esp. against undead). But these were not my usual role. On the other hand knowing that you can do them in a pinch and knowing how to do them as effectively as possible can be a literal life saver, as well as make for a fun group experience. In all things, good communication with your group is key. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/urobingoodfellow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Robin Goodfellow</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 234<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/23/02 3:06:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=398.topic&index=46>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Effective roleplaying</span><hr size=1> I find myself in a unique situation with regards to Snare lately.<br>
<br>
I've been fighting on Luclin an awful lot, and a lot of things (read: everything?) seems to resist it every time I cast it.  Not 90% of the time, but every time.  However, those that resist Snare don't seem to resist the new Ranger 1st level Tangling Weeds at all.  So I've been letting the Rangers do that.<br>
<br>
I haven't yet figured out why that is, but for the time being, while fighting where I am, I've dispensed with Snare.  I know how valuable it is, but if it doesn't land, it's no use burning time and mana trying.<br>
<br>
